+Audit trail of each rotation is emitted as a structured log line from
+`rotate_secret` itself (one line per rotation: actor, secret name, old
+version, new version, ttl, timestamp). We do **not** extend [[ft002]] with
+a new audit-log channel — see [Out of scope](#out-of-scope).
+
+## plan
+
+### Affected components
+
+- `src/lib/vault.py` — add `rotate_secret(name, value, ttl_seconds=300)`
+  helper; keep `secret(name)` read path untouched (consumer contract is
+  the [[ft002]] api_surface).
+- New CLI entry under `src/lib/` (or a sibling script) that platform-engineer
+  invokes to perform a rotation against a single secret name.
+- No service-side code changes. Reports / auth / metrics keep calling
+  `secret(name)` unchanged — that is the whole point of the overlap window.
+
+### File tree (proposed)
+
+```
+src/lib/
+  vault.py               # extended: rotate_secret() added
+  vault_rotate_cli.py    # new: thin CLI wrapper (argparse → rotate_secret)
+tests/lib/
+  test_vault_rotate.py   # new: unit + overlap-window tests
+```
+
+### Conventions
+
+- Stay within [[ft002]]'s existing single read path (`secret(name)`); do
+  not introduce a second client surface.
+- Rotation is one-secret-at-a-time. Bulk rotation is out of scope for
+  this spec (file as a follow-up story if needed).
+- TTL is a **per-call argument**, defaulting to 300s. No module-level
+  state, no global default mutator. Matches the [[ft002]] "no local
+  data_model" contract — TTL lives in Vault, not in our code.
+- Audit log is a structured line emitted via the standard logging
+  module (JSON formatter already used by services). One log line per
+  successful rotation, one per failure. No new feature, no new sink.
+
+### Known limitations
+
+- Synthetic-check coverage relies on the existing platform-engineer
+  smoke test invoking each service's health endpoint every 30s during
+  the rotation window. If that smoke test isn't already in place, the
+  acceptance criterion "no 5xx during rotation" can only be verified
+  manually for this spec.
+- Vault must already support versioned aliases for the secrets we
+  rotate. Secrets that predate the alias convention need a one-time
+  migration; that migration is out of scope here.
+
+### Out of scope
+
+These were drafted into the `## solution` during spec-writing but
+rejected during refinement:
+
+- **`vault.set_default_ttl(seconds=300)` global knob.** Reasons: (1)
+  not part of [[ft002]] api_surface; widening a stable Feature for one
+  consumer's convenience is exactly what the AKM Feature lifecycle
+  warns against; (2) introduces module-level state that makes the
+  overlap window invisible at call sites and untestable in isolation;
+  (3) per-call TTL covers every real use case. If a future story needs
+  a different default, the right answer is a new Feature or a
+  superseding Implementation — not a hidden global.
+- **Audit-log channel on [[ft002]].** [[ft002]] currently has no
+  audit-log surface; bolting one on for this spec would widen a stable
+  Feature's contract for a single consumer. Structured logging from
+  `rotate_secret` covers the requirement (security team can grep /
+  ship logs centrally as they do today). If a real cross-cutting
+  audit-log story emerges (e.g. `us005` quarterly audit-log export),
+  it should mint its own `ft###` — *that* is the moment to design an
+  audit-log Feature, not now.
+
+## tasks
+
+### Task 1: Add `rotate_secret` helper to `src/lib/vault.py`
+
+#### type
+feature
+
+#### effort
+3h
+
+#### depends
+- — none
+
+#### files_touched
+- `src/lib/vault.py`
+
+#### success_criteria
+- Function signature: `rotate_secret(name: str, value: str, ttl_seconds: int = 300) -> RotationResult`
+- Stages the new value under a fresh version alias in Vault.
+- Returns previous version id, new version id, and the ttl applied.
+- Leaves prior version readable via `secret(name)` for `ttl_seconds` after the call.
+- Raises `VaultRotationError` (new exception) on Vault API failure;
+  does not partially commit.
+
+#### edge_cases
+- Secret name does not exist yet → raise `VaultRotationError` (do not
+  silently create — rotation is for existing secrets).
+- Vault returns a non-2xx during the write → no version flip happens;
+  prior version remains the only readable value.
+- `ttl_seconds <= 0` → reject with `ValueError` (would defeat the
+  overlap guarantee).
+- Caller passes `ttl_seconds > 86400` → log a warning but allow (some
+  services may want a longer migration window).
+
+#### test_plan
+- `test_rotate_secret_happy_path` — stages new version, prior version
+  still readable, returns both version ids.
+- `test_rotate_secret_missing_secret` — raises `VaultRotationError`.
+- `test_rotate_secret_partial_failure` — simulate Vault write 500;
+  assert no flip and prior version still readable.
+- `test_rotate_secret_invalid_ttl_zero` — raises `ValueError`.
+- `test_rotate_secret_invalid_ttl_negative` — raises `ValueError`.
+
+### Task 2: Emit structured audit log line per rotation
+
+#### type
+feature
+
+#### effort
+1h
+
+#### depends
+- Task 1
+
+#### files_touched
+- `src/lib/vault.py`
+
+#### success_criteria
+- On successful rotation, `rotate_secret` emits one structured log
+  line at INFO level: `{event: "vault.secret.rotated", name, prior_version,
+  new_version, ttl_seconds, actor, ts}`.
+- On `VaultRotationError`, emit one structured log line at ERROR level
+  with the same fields minus `new_version`, plus `error`.
+- `actor` resolves from `VAULT_ROTATION_ACTOR` env var; falls back to
+  `os.getlogin()`; never blocks rotation if actor cannot be resolved
+  (emit `actor: "unknown"`).
+
+#### edge_cases
+- Logger is misconfigured / not initialized → rotation must still
+  succeed; log failure must not propagate.
+- `os.getlogin()` raises in containerized environments (no controlling
+  tty) → falls back to `unknown` rather than crashing.
+
+#### test_plan
+- `test_audit_log_success_shape` — capture log records, assert all
+  required fields present.
+- `test_audit_log_failure_shape` — same but for the error path.
+- `test_audit_log_actor_resolution` — env var wins over `os.getlogin`;
+  both missing → `unknown`.
+
+### Task 3: CLI wrapper `vault_rotate_cli.py`
+
+#### type
+feature
+
+#### effort
+2h
+
+#### depends
+- Task 1
+
+#### files_touched
+- `src/lib/vault_rotate_cli.py` (new)
+
+#### success_criteria
+- Argparse interface: `python -m acme.lib.vault_rotate_cli --name <n>
+  --value-from-stdin [--ttl 300]`.
+- Reads the new value from stdin (never from argv — would land in
+  shell history).
+- Exits 0 on success, 1 on `VaultRotationError`, 2 on argument error.
+- Prints the audit log line to stderr for operator visibility (in
+  addition to logger emission).
+
+#### edge_cases
+- Stdin is a tty (interactive run with no piped input) → prompt with
+  getpass, do not echo.
+- Empty value piped on stdin → reject with exit code 2.
+- `--ttl` non-integer → argparse rejects with exit code 2.
+
+#### test_plan
+- `test_cli_happy_path_pipe` — pipe a value, assert exit 0 and
+  rotation called once with the right args.
+- `test_cli_empty_stdin` — assert exit 2, no rotation call.
+- `test_cli_vault_failure_exit_code` — patch `rotate_secret` to raise,
+  assert exit 1.
+- `test_cli_argv_does_not_carry_value` — guard against accidentally
+  adding a `--value` flag in the future.
+
+### Task 4: Overlap-window integration test against a vault stub
+
+#### type
+task
+
+#### effort
+3h
+
+#### depends
+- Task 1
+
+#### files_touched
+- `tests/lib/test_vault_rotate.py`
+
+#### success_criteria
+- Spin up an in-process Vault stub (fixture) supporting versioned
+  aliases + TTL expiry.
+- After `rotate_secret(name, new, ttl_seconds=2)`:
+  - `secret(name)` returns the new value immediately.
+  - `secret(name)` still returns the **prior** value when explicitly
+    asked for the prior version id (proves both versions live during
+    overlap).
+  - After 2s, the stub expires the prior version; reading by prior
+    version id raises.
+- No 5xx surfaced through `secret(name)` at any point during the
+  window — the read path is the [[ft002]] contract and must stay 200.
+
+#### edge_cases
+- Stub clock skew: use a controllable clock fixture, not `time.sleep`,
+  to keep the test deterministic and fast.
+- Rotation called twice in quick succession on the same secret →
+  second call still respects the first call's overlap (no
+  cliff-cutting the prior version).
+
+#### test_plan
+- `test_overlap_window_both_versions_readable` — covers the main
+  acceptance criterion.
+- `test_overlap_window_expires_after_ttl` — virtual clock advance.
+- `test_double_rotation_preserves_prior_overlap` — two
+  back-to-back rotations.
